Different Between Base and Head
================================================================================
🧩 What --base and --head are

    --base: The commit SHA that Nx should treat as the “starting point” (the old state of your code).
    --head: The commit SHA that Nx should treat as the “ending point” (the new state of your code).
Nx compares these two commits to figure out what changed. From that diff, it determines which projects are “affected.”
🔧 Why $NX_BASE and $NX_HEAD
    In CI, you don’t want to hardcode commit SHAs.
The action nrwl/nx-set-shas automatically sets environment variables:
$NX_BASE → the commit you’re comparing against (usually the branch you’re merging into, like origin/main).
  $NX_HEAD → the commit you just pushed (the tip of your PR or branch).

    By passing --base=$NX_BASE --head=$NX_HEAD, you’re telling Nx:
    “Look at the changes between these two commits and only run tasks for affected projects.”

🌟 Elementary analogy
Imagine you’re comparing two versions of a school notebook:
  Base = yesterday’s version of the notebook.
   Head = today’s version after you added new notes.
    Nx flips through the pages to see what changed between yesterday and today, then only re‑checks the homework assignments (projects) that were touched.
