Here’s the visual diagram you asked for — it shows how Nx walks the dependency graph between the **base commit** and the **head commit** to figure out which projects are affected.  

On the left, you see the **Base Commit (Original State)** — all projects and shared libraries before your changes. On the right, the **Head Commit (New Changes)** — after you’ve modified files. Nx compares these two graphs:

- 🔴 **Changed nodes** → projects or libraries you directly edited.  
- 🟠 **Affected nodes** → projects that depend on those changed ones.  
- ⚪ **Unaffected nodes** → projects untouched by the change.

So if you modify a shared library, Nx traces every app that depends on it and marks them as “affected.” That’s why multiple apps can show up even if you only changed one file.

This dependency‑graph walk is what makes Nx’s CI intelligent — it doesn’t just look at file paths, it understands relationships between projects.  

